<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Slurring" class="currentChild" href="Slurring">Slurring</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A printing defect characterized by the smearing of the trailing edges of a printed impression, which is typically caused by slippage of the paper, resulting—in <a title="Offset Lithography" href="Offset_Lithography">offset lithography</a>, for example—from increased pressure between the plate and the <a title="Blanket" href="Blanket">blanket</a> or between the blanket and the paper. It can also be caused by using a loose blanket, too soft a blanket, too soft an ink, or by the excessive use of ink. It can also be generated by using deformed paper, such as paper with <a title="Wavy Edges" href="Wavy_Edges">wavy edges</a> or other distortions. When slurring occurs in halftone images, it is called <a title="Dot Slurring" href="Dot_Slurring">dot slurring</a>. (See also <a title="Doubling" href="Doubling">Doubling</a>.) 
</p>
